    <section id="warnings">
      <h2>Warnings</h2>
      <ContentBox type="warning" title={`Warning: "Just Be Happy" Is Not the Answer`}>
        The research showing that happiness predates success is sometimes misread as a license to pursue happiness at the expense of achievement. This is a mistake. The research shows that well-being and achievement are mutually reinforcing when success is pursued with genuine engagement and meaning. It does not show that you can replace ambitious effort with positive thinking. Happiness without growth often leads to stagnation and, ultimately, less well-being.
      </ContentBox>
      <ContentBox type="warning" title="Warning: Comparing Your Happiness to Others Is Especially Destructive">
        Social comparison — the tendency to evaluate your own success and happiness against others — is one of the strongest predictors of reduced well-being across cultures. Social media has dramatically intensified this tendency by providing constant curated glimpses of others' highlights. Defining your success in terms of your own values and trajectory, rather than relative to others, is essential for sustainable well-being.
      </ContentBox>
      <ContentBox type="warning" title="Warning: Forced Positivity Can Mask Important Signals">
        Not all negative emotions are problems to be solved. Sadness, frustration, and dissatisfaction are often meaningful signals about values violations, unmet needs, or directions worth changing. The goal is not to maintain constant happiness but to develop emotional intelligence — the ability to understand and work with the full range of your emotional life, including its darker textures, in service of a genuinely flourishing existence.
      </ContentBox>
    </section>

